Upper Newport Bay, Newport Beach, CA. 21 Oct. 2005. ©  Most members of this family are found in Asia and , but this species is also found in the subtropical areas of Florida, Texas, and California. It may have been introduced from Asia. It feeds on insects and is harmless although it can give a painful bite. It can also be scary because of its large size, its quick movements, its ability to run sideways, and its ability to run up glass and other smooth surfaces! This one, which was found in a truck and may have come from further south, is missing a leg.
Female. La Habra Heights, Orange County, CA. 4/28/14. © Lenny Vincent.

Distinguishing characters from : body elongated and covered with golden scales; pair of white bars, often with black slash or block-like mark on either side, just anterior to the spinnerets on the dorsal surface; legs red-brown with lighter ventral distal patellae and whole tarsi. Thanks to Tim Manolis for help with identification.

spider_description: This spectacular orb-weaving spider is common in Southern California in the Summer and Fall, especially on prickly-pear plants. The male is much smaller than the female. The spider includes zig-zag structures called stabilimenta in the orb web, probably in order to make it more visible to birds who might otherwise fly into it accidentally and destroy it. Their webs are sometimes occupied by commensal .
